    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "A photon passes an excited atom and keeps going \u2014 then two identical photons emerge, same direction, same phase.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Why One Photon Can Become Two Identical Twins",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "title"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.42,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 7,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Atoms have two energy levels. A photon of exactly the right energy can be absorbed, lifting the atom up. Later, the atom falls and emits a photon \u2014 but in a random direction. This is spontaneous emission.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.87,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 20,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Classical theory predicts only this: absorb and spontaneously re-emit. A brighter input means more emissions, but each photon fires randomly. No coherence, no directionality. Why does a laser beam exist at all?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Absorption predicts random re-emission. A laser beam is not random. Why?",
        "style": "question"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.52,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 29,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "Einstein in 1917 found a third process hidden in the thermodynamics. When a photon passes an already-excited atom, it can trigger the atom to emit a second photon \u2014 coherent with the first: same direction, same phase, same frequency.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.78,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 43,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4,
      "narration_text": "The mechanism: stimulated emission.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "A passing photon triggers an exact copy of itself.",
        "style": "section"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.35,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 47,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "The two photons are not just similar \u2014 they are quantum-coherent. They carry the same phase relationship. Each copy can trigger more copies. If excited atoms outnumber ground-state atoms \u2014 population inversion \u2014 the signal multiplies.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "duplicate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.91,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 61,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "Population inversion requires pumping \u2014 driving more atoms up than down. In thermal equilibrium the lower level is always more populated. Inversion is non-equilibrium, maintained by continuous energy input.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.87,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 75,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "Once inversion exists, each photon spawns copies faster than they are absorbed. The light avalanches. Theodore Maiman demonstrated this in 1960 in ruby \u2014 the first laser.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "Once inversion exists, each photon spawns copies faster than they are\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B08.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.12,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 88,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Stimulated photons are coherent: they interfere constructively and build into a single directional beam. Spontaneous photons scatter in all directions and wash out. The laser beam is the coherent avalanche, not the random drizzle.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.45,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 99,
      "estimated_duration_s": 3,
      "narration_text": "Coherence is the signal; spontaneity is the noise.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Stimulated copies add. Spontaneous emissions scatter.",
        "style": "implication"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.11,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 102,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4,
      "narration_text": "The worked example.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "One seed photon, three atoms, one chain",
        "style": "example"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.2,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 106,
      "estimated_duration_s": 22,
      "narration_text": "Illustrative numbers: one seed photon enters a medium with three excited atoms. It triggers atom 1 \u2014 two photons. Those two trigger atoms 2 and 3 \u2014 four photons. Four coherent photons emerge where one entered, all pointing the same direction. Double the atoms, double the output per pass. This is gain.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 20.61,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 128,
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "narration_text": "Why does one photon become two? Because quantum mechanics allows an excited atom to be triggered by a passing photon \u2014 and the triggered emission is a perfect quantum copy. That copy-on-demand is the laser principle. QUANTUM MECHANICS.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "A passing photon triggers an exact coherent copy \u2014 that is why a laser exists.",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "recap"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.464,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-stimulated-laser/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-stimulated-laser/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
